  "description": "¶What this lesson covers How HTML gives structure and meaning to documents, why that structure matters, and how the choice of markup shapes what a document can communicate.\n¶Prerequisites Familiarity with web pages as a reader. No prior knowledge of HTML is assumed.\n¶Documents before the web Before hypertext, most documents were designed for a single rendering: a printed page. Structure — headings, paragraphs, lists, emphasis — was conveyed through visual formatting. A heading was a heading because it was set in a larger typeface, not because the document declared it to be one.\n",
